text: I've noticed this since the first trailer for this film, but the whole concept of "Your inner circle has been compromised, we are on the brink of war, trust no one" is literally the core of Winter Soldier's premise. While the themes might not be the same in terms of being haunted by the ghosts of your past and unknowingly serving the evil you fought against, there is major overlap and Marvel was trying to cash in on the success from Winter Soldier as their best movie to save themselves. I'll still watch this since the The Winter Soldier is an all time favorite of mine, but I hope it has some originality and can still be good.

text:
Positives : 
Gal Gadot look stunning.
Zegler can sing.

Negatives.
You tried to hide it, but you can still tell that this is a girl boss movie. 
Thematically this would not be an issue but, unfortunately the actress playing Snow White made it impossible to separate the character from the actress. 

She might have very well played the best Snow White on screen but many will see a "Mean, Disrespectful, and very Unlikeable" person as Snow White.
That will ultimately hurt sales for this movie.

The CG in the movie looks really good in certain scenes, but more often then not, pulls you out of immersion with really bad uncanny valley images. The Dwarves in particular just didn't quite translate well during the animation process, they really should have used live actors.

All in all, hope that those who can enjoy this movie will do so, for me, Snow White's departure from the true innocent as portrayed in the original movie and the radical change to the story (and in essence, the soul of this story) is just too much of a stretch and neither I nor my family will be supporting it.

text: I remember seeing scar's paw come crashing down in the theater opening night in a packed theater in 1994. We had all just finished watching the circle of life scene and were still not sold on the film we were all like what the heck is this movie musical about lions? The movie changed my life at the time and still resonates to this day. I can watch it again and again and can recite the entire movie in the voice of the characters w/o a script. text: For those who don't know: Bong Joon Ho is one of the best directors in the world, straight up. He rivals Park Chan Wook as the best director working in South Korea. His best movie is Memories of Murder, but he's also made several others including The Host, Snowpiercer, Okja, and Parasite. His movies are known for being disturbing and representing the dark side of humanity, but this one seems like he's going for a dark comedy/satirical approach which could work really well. I would strongly recommend watching his earlier movies so you can understand his vibe.

text: The movie initially had fascinating visuals and an intriguing atmosphere. However, the characters, especially the villain, felt too one-dimensional. The director seemed to aim for a metaphorical meaning, but it ended up feeling too boring and unengaging. Because of this, the story felt loose and predictable, making it easy to guess the ending. Reflecting on it now, the topic also feels too old-fashioned because there are already so many stories about cloning, and the director's effort to deliver that concept didn't resonate with me.

text: I liked the concept. It was creative. But it was bizarre like the Hitchhiker's Guide and seemingly without purpose as in the Guide. There were parallels to our life and death, but it lost the truthful angst of the question in its absurdist presentation. Obviously there was a moral to the story, about personal responsibility, coexistence vs ignorant violence and abuse. But the scenes with the leader, seemingly trying to depict someone we know, spoiled serious contemplation. Although it was fantastical, it lent itself to be more of a drama, a drama which stalled on a single storyline when the expendables idea could have continued bringing in fresh plot twists. Yet it didn't. The Menu had extreme unlikely activity but it stayed real so we could sink ourselves into the idea. If Mickey was to just be odd and quirky with cartoon co-stars it needed to go even farther. Even cartoons evolve with incredible imagination. Either way it didn't invest. You can't just make up for a missing movie by playing simplistic narration and being grotesque.

text: It seems like they made this trailer in response to the complaints of the previous one. The only line Kraven has is in russian this time, which conceals that he has no accent whatsoever. Not sure what to believe here, but the first trailer probably has more reality in it.

text:
Way, way, WAY, better than expected! Sophie Thatcher has had her watershed moment. With this she is certainly on EVERYONE radar. She is the standout in an also excellent cast, the foil to Jack Quaids self-serving boorish, manipulative lout of a man-boy. (props to him as well) Its been a while since I have seen naivety, innocence, and vulnerability, contrasted with confidence and sense of purpose in Sophie as "Iris the Companion".
Certainly she sticks the landing, and also creates a compelling character, that I do hope we see more of in a possible sequel.

I have an amazing story. One day I was driving home, when all of a sudden the Lord came to me in spirit. I felt very close to Him. I knew if I asked him to play any song on the radio he would, I guess to bless my faith.
So I said "ok, Lord play "Come as you are". 
I turned on the radio and the song started playing right there on the spot, perfectly‚Ä¶
I started getting flooded with chills like a waterfall, crying, and trembling. 
He stayed with me for 10 minutes in my driveway. until I got outta the car.

Someone is using the monkey as a weapon, or the monkey is using them as an assistant. This implies they know what‚Äôs it‚Äôs doing, which further implies that they brought it there knowing it would kill. text:
Where do I even begin? Oh, right, the exploding people. Yes, you read that correctly. Not just one exploding person, mind you, but a veritable symphony of exploding people. It's like the filmmakers decided to replace character development with a fireworks display of gore. And the gore? Let's just say it looked like they raided the clearance aisle of a Halloween prop store.

The script? It's less a script and more a collection of random grunts, screams, and the occasional, "Where's the monkey?" Said monkey, by the way, is a plush and plastic toy that apparently possesses the power to turn humans into fleshy pi√±atas. No explanation, no backstory, just... splat. It's like the writers were playing a game of Mad Libs with a horror movie plot and the results were, shall we say, "unique."

And the editing? Oh, the editing. They seem to have taken inspiration from a blender. We're treated to a rapid-fire montage of limbs, torsos, and close-ups of eyeballs, all set to a soundtrack that sounds like a dial-up modem having a seizure. It's less a movie and more a visual assault on the senses.

The "plot" (again, using that word generously) revolves around... well, I'm not entirely sure. Something about a cursed monkey toy and a group of people who apparently won a contest to see who could make the worst life choices. The acting is on par with a high school play performed by sleepwalkers.

Honestly, I'm baffled. I'm genuinely perplexed as to how this film got made. Did someone accidentally fund a fever dream? Did a group of toddlers take over a film set? I have so many questions, and none of them involve the monkey.

"Monkey" isn't just bad; it's an insult to bad movies. It's the cinematic equivalent of a moldy sandwich left in a hot car. It's a testament to the fact that sometimes, money is indeed wasted. If you value your sanity, your time, or your ability to enjoy any other movie ever made, stay far, far away from "Monkey." You've been warned.

Some producers never learn.  And if denzel's $$ is behind the decision to compete with the original _gladiator,_ then he's overdue for a hard lesson himself

Their 24 year wait proves that what theyre banking on is two younger generations who dont give a d*** about remaining authentic.  They dont care whether this new film successfully carries or at least respects the weight & meaning of what came before.  These producers full well know theyre abandoning the original _gladiator's_ authenticity AND therefore three entire earlier generations that will never forget it:

1.  You cant outdo an original.  Making the attempt is guaranteed failure

2.  If youre going to make a sequel, retain as many of the following as possible:

original director
original screenwriter(s)
original actors

If people cant see this is true about the star wars legacy, then its hopeless.  Theyve learned nothing valuable from what theyve watched

text: Gladiator 2 is grossly overrated‚Äîfrankly, it‚Äôs bad. The script is poorly written, the dialogues are uninspired, and the story feels contrived. The idea of making Lucius the son of Maximus is nonsensical and reeks of desperation to force Maximus‚Äô legacy into the sequel. The narrative is clunky and lacks the seamless flow of the original. Worse still, the fantastical addition of fighting sharks in the Colosseum is absurd and undermines the grounded realism that made the first film great. To top it off, the actor playing Lucius is far less charismatic than Russell Crowe, leaving the sequel feeling hollow. The director should have taken a more original approach instead of lazily attempting to replicate the magic of the first movie.

text:
There's a reason why this is the most acclaimed manhwa/web novel in the world, and why so many try to replicate it, and fail. This story concluded just before covid 19, give or take 8 months. Meaning people could watch it from start to finish in one sitting if they wanted to, and didn't have to wait for new parts.

There is also the solid pacing, which some try to say is terrible, its pacing is far better than even something like DB, which is mostly filler from one fight to the next.

This is literally bottled lightning. Good show

text: The movie was a delight, lots of fan service with things comic book fans always wanted to see on screen, some fun nostalgia,  unexpected twists on the cameos(crazy how none of that leaked!), and nice digs at how bad the MCU fell off after Infinity War.  I really wanted to enjoy it, so was glad it turned out so well even when it had to slog through the sludge that was the multiverse aspects that everyone is sick of, and never liked in the first place.  I haven't liked anything Marvel since Infinity War, but I liked this.  So kudos for making a movie for the fans, well done.

text: Would not be surprised if Mikey wins MTV movie awards for best kiss, fight sequence, scared as shit performance (by actress), and best actress, and if Anora wins best picture; it's a love story that becomes an emotional thrill ride almost midway through.  I was praying to god she wouldn't have to deal with annulment of this ultimately fraud marriage.  It seemed like "Pretty Woman" in search of a happy ending for all parties involved; it ultimately gets sort of one.  In the ending, I felt she was about to make out with (if not have sex with) Igor; she was crying tears in the realization that she was back to her regular job as sex worker, tears of joy over having gotten a memento or souvenir of the marriage that should have been (drunkenness notwithstanding), but at least I got an ending that reminded me of the ending of "Indecent Proposal", and that she got away with $25000 from Vanya and Igor.  I loved the love story part of the movie's first 3/8th though; during the next 3/8th, it needlessly becomes a drama where I hoped Vanya would get help, but he was afraid of being caught by his disapproving parents, Nikolai and especially Galina.  The next 1/8th of the film involves the marriage annulment (which I didn't feel should have happened).  Turns out Vanya married a bitch whose parents were likewise afraid of their son's wife's profession.  Though I enjoyed this wild, profane blast, I preferred "Pretty Woman" a little more, but I still give this movie a 8 out of 10.

text:
SPOLIER ALERT. READ IF YOU HAVE WATCHED THE MOVIE






my opinion : 
the movie started out pretty raw and real. the dialogue the characters were having felt so real unlike typical movie lines. it felt like you are watching a cctv footage of real people. and then comes evan. started out as expected , chill casual and everything. but wtf ? how did she think he was fr when he asked to marry her ? i thought her reaction would be like r u serious and like this is my job to please people. but she just accepted the proposal. and when torus and guys confronted them, she was acting like this marriage was real and she was defending it with all her might. her acting felt very good like real person would react in that situation.

then came court scene. turns out marriage cant be annuled if married in nevada. after being thrown out of court, she was trying to convince him to stay together and brother was not ggiving 2 fks. at that point. i closed it. i didnt want to watch anymore of that. 

trust me the acting was amazing but the plot was not it.

edit :
ok i watched it and that divorce scene was hilarious. that comeback anora gave to evan's mother was crazy lol. 
but the plane scene was predictable. i knew evan was not really in love with her. he bought her with money. fked her and partied with her. but never treated her like a lover would.

and to some people saying sad ending , nope, atleast not for me. yeah sad she got hurt but that hug by igor to her was real. since the moment igor was introduced in the movie, he had been nice to her all along.

text: Every time Hollywood tells a story of a female protagonist who survives, thrives and triumphs based on inherent feminine traits such as familial love, kindness and nurturing, they create a banger. text: My absolute favorite part of the movie is when the emotions realize, specifically joy, that Riley needs all of it to truly form a truthful perception of the person she really is. The good, the bad, the best, the worst, all of it. We can't push the worst of us to the back of our heads and only focus on the best parts of us. To live a life where anxiety doesn't control every aspect of our life, we need to embrace every part of ourselves. Loving yourself is incredibly hard, and it's something that is completely impossible if you keep pushing the worst parts of yourself out of sight and out of mind. The dam will burst eventually. The first step to truly finding your true self is embracing your true self. It's not quite as emotional as the first movie, in my opinion, but it has a message that is definitely just as important of a message to hear. I loved Inside Out 2! 9/10!

text: Saw this movie a couple weeks ago with one of my closest friends. We both have read the books since elementary school and are now seeing it while in high school. text: A few months ago, before I made my channel, I found a captain underpants iceberg video and one thing that caught my attention was a part about a dog man movie. A few months after I watched that video, this came out. As a recent dog man reader, I have had an obsession with the series from book 1. I genuinely love how the characters sound, look, and how vibrant the movie is. This could really capture an audience. I also love how they made the news reporter have an australian accent because in dog man and cat kid, when Yolay said "Hooray for Italy!" in italian, the news reporter says "But I'm Australian." I have so much genuine excitement for this movie. I love how the style of the eyes reference the eye style from the captain underpants movie. The cartoony style/vibe/feel/look make the trailer look 100 times better. Petey's lab looks like how it does in the book. Petey seems like such a villain in the movie especially when the news reporter lady says "How evil can one cat be!?" and Petey says "Pretty Evil!" Can't wait, and I be at the theater in a heartbeat on January 31st 2025.

text:
I first saw these when I was a youngster in the 70s. I was enthralled beyond words. I've seen "The Godfather" and its sequel "The Godfather Part II" countless times, and I swear that each time I view them I learn or discover something new. Strangely, I learned to appreciate these movies even more so because of my love of the "Star Wars" films, I kid you not. Permit me to explain... 

I remember watching the two people who were arguably considered the greatest movie reviewers ever: Gene Siskel and Roger Ebert. When "The Empire Strikes Back" came out in 1980, I remember both Gene and Roger discussing how they both believed that movie was up there with The Godfather Part II as the two greatest sequels ever produced. When I first heard that, I immediately thought they were nuts. One movie was a science fiction space action movie, while the other was a fictional tale of a Mafia family, but complete with almost non-fiction allusions to reality. 

Gene and Roger explained why they thought they were both so good. One of the main reasons was that both of the sequels ended in tragedy, sadness, and despair. The Godfather Part II saw Michael murder his own brother, while The Empire Strikes Back saw Darth Vader almost kill his own son; he cut off his son's arm. Vader also captured and immobilized Han Solo, handing him off to another evil individual. In both movies there were also a number of other deaths occuring around those main ones. In short, both movies defied the conventional good-guys-beat-the-bad-guys plot and ending. 

In doing so, these two sequels caused a lot of people to think, perhaps ask questions, rhetorical or otherwise, and not just about whether there would be another sequel to follow. Of course we know the answer to that, as The Return of the Jedi premiered in May 1983 and The Godfather Part III premiered in December 1990.

As I got older, I began to relook at these movies, the sequels included, in a different light, one that went beyond typical cinematic presentation. I also began to pay more attention to and thoroughly enjoy movie scores (their soundtracks), which in turn led to me enjoy orchestral music and concerts. First Nina Rota then John Williams helped me to appreciate the artistry behind an orchestra, its musicians, and their musical pieces. For that and more I can thank the true geniuses behind two movies that were from two genres that were about as far apart on the spectrum one would think.

text:
RESTORATION DETAILS
Over 300 cartons of film were scrutinized to find the best possible resolution for every frame of all three films.
Over 4,000 hours were spent repairing film stains, tears, and other anomalies in the negatives.
Over 1,000 hours were spent on rigorous color correction to ensure the high dynamic range tools were respectful of the original vision of Coppola and cinematographer Gordon Willis.
In addition to the 5.1 audio approved by Walter Murch in 2007, the original mono tracks on he Godfather and The Godfather: Part II have been restored.
All work was overseen by Coppola.

text:
As much as I love BR2049 (it's my personal No.1 movie of all time, actually), this trailer and the whole marketing campaign back when I came out didn't do it justice. The film is slow, calm, and basically a character drama; while the marketing painted it as a mere action blockbuster set in the BR universe with an old actor reprising his role as a catalyst for expositions, usual franshise images.
Blade Runner 2049 deserves more love, and anyone who love cinema should give it a decent watch, with the biggest screen and best audio set they can get. Movies like it were the reasons theaters shouldn't be replace with home streaming services.

text:
The life lessons I got from the Shawkshank Redemption -

1. Hope is Powerful: The film emphasizes that hope can sustain us through even the toughest times. Andy Dufresne's unwavering hope ultimately leads to his freedom.


2. Perseverance: Andy's determination to improve his situation, despite the odds, teaches the importance of resilience and hard work.


3. Friendship: The bond between Andy and Red highlights the value of companionship and loyalty in overcoming adversity.


4. Integrity and Morality: Andy maintains his principles in a corrupt environment, illustrating that integrity is crucial, even when it‚Äôs difficult.


5. The Importance of Freedom: The story underscores the human desire for freedom and self-determination, reminding us to cherish our liberties.


6. Redemption: Everyone has the potential for change and redemption, showing that past mistakes do not define us.
author: @brucewayne24783
clean_text: the life lessons i got from the shawkshank redemption 1. hope is powerful the film emphasizes that hope can sustain us through even the toughest times. andy dufresnes unwavering hope ultimately leads to his freedom. 2. perseverance andys determination to improve his situation, despite the odds, teaches the importance of resilience and hard work. 3. friendship the bond between andy and red highlights the value of companionship and loyalty in overcoming adversity. 4. integrity and morality andy maintains his principles in a corrupt environment, illustrating that integrity is crucial, even when it is difficult. 5. the importance of freedom the story underscores the human desire for freedom and selfdetermination, reminding us to cherish our liberties. 6. redemption everyone has the potential for change and redemption, showing that past mistakes do not define us.

text:
I couldn‚Äôt help but think about the potential scientific implications of what happened to the diver. The extreme cold, lack of oxygen, and near-death experience he survived reminded me of the concept of a cryogenic or hibernation chamber. It felt as if his body was placed in a suspended state‚Äîone where he should have died, yet somehow, he didn‚Äôt.

This made me wonder if deep-sea diving incidents like this could contribute to research. If we could understand how the body endures such conditions, maybe we could develop real-world cryogenic technology for space travel or medical use. ‚ò∫

text:
My Review (from Letterboxd):

Based on a CHILLING true story and the documentary of the same name, of the underwater accident that left Chris Lemons with only 10 minutes of oxygen and 29 in physical and mental limbo without it, as Duncan Alloc, Dave Yuasa, and the rest of the ship crew have to rescue him. A VERY well directed, PHENOMENALLY edited, WONDERFULLY acted, and MASTERFULLY scored and shot movie. Alex Parkinson knocked it out of the park with how much emotion and tension he was able to balance scene by scene. The editing, including one moment where the audio abruptly cuts, and cuts HARD, leaving us in silence, and then drifting back in, also remarkable. Paul Leonard-Morgan‚Äôs soundtrack also hit right where it needed to in those moments of tension, emotion, and overall atmosphere. As did the cinematography, which handles a cutting back and forth between sea cameras and our own perspective well. Overall, a great start for me when beginning to review movies for 2025. 5/5 stars.

text: This came out when I was in my second year of film school, and our instructor lectured us on how this movie would do poorly and be quickly forgotten, all because it was shot with a (highish end) consumer video camera.  Aside from being an awesome, well received, and lovingly remembered film, it made consumer quality cameras that much more viable as a filmmaking medium.

text:

text: Here's something interesting about this undead classic, Danny Boyle had denied the movie being a zombie flick, although people had found it to be one anyway. This was because the virus made the infected insanely mad with bloodlust and rage (think of rabies). The infected also feel homicidal as opposed to being cannibalistic, and are fast like World War Z. The movie's threat leans more to the Crazies, a movie whose virus makes people brutalize each other like with 28 Days Later, and although people who get attacked by the infected get injured/wounded, they do not die and reanimate like zombies, they quickly become one of the infected without reanimation via biting or through direct contact with contaminated blood. The Sadness, a Taiwanese splatterfest about people being infected feeling ecstatic with homicidal thoughts, is adjacent to both movies, just don't watch if you are a gore hater, but unless you have read the Crossed and enjoy the edgy tone of the series, this is the closest thing to an adaptation because of its gratuitous violence.

You don't insert off genre in everything like hiphop or RnB (Hear that, Tick Tick Boom?) you don't use too much CGI (hear that, Cats?) AND!
